Title : Hakija Hadžić
Text : '''Hakija Hadžić''' (1883&ndash;1953) was [[Herzegovina|Herzegovinian]] Muslim politician who belonged to the group of Muslim politicians from Bosnia, who nationally felt Croats and approached the [[Ustaše|Ustasha movement]]. Hadžić belonged to a group of Muslim politicians who held pro-Croatian position in the interwar period. 

== Interwar period ==
Hadžić was a politician who had the strongest influence on Muslim population of [[Yugoslavia]] before the [[Second World War]].<ref name="Vasić1995">{{cite book|last=Vasić|first=Milan|authorlink=Milan Vasić|title=Bosna i Hercegovina od srednjeg veka do novijeg vremena: međunarodni naučni skup 13-15. decembar 1994|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=m2MtAQAAIAAJ|year=1995|publisher=Istorijski institut SANU|page=119|quote=Највише утицаја на муслиманско становништво измећу два рата имао је вођа ЈМО др Мехмед Спахо, а пред рат Хакија Хаџић и други.}}</ref> Before 1938 elections Hadžić established new political party (Croatian Muslim Peasant Party) which had received very modest support at the elections.<ref name="Papić1985">{{cite book|last=Papić|first=Radovan|title=Hercegovina u revoluciji: sjećanja, analize, dokumenti|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tcEfAAAAMAAJ|year=1985|publisher=NIŠRO "Oslobođenje"|page=72|quote= Jos uoci iz- bora 1938. godine Hakija Hadzic je organizovao novu stranku...}}</ref>

== Second World War ==
As personal friend of Ante Pavelić, he promoted Ustaša politics in regions of Herzegovina and Bosnia.<ref name="Tomasevich">{{cite book|last=Tomasevich|first=Jozo|authorlink=Jozo Tomasevich|title=War and Revolution in Yugoslavia: 1941 - 1945|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fqUSGevFe5MC&pg=PA491|publisher=Stanford University Press|isbn=978-0-8047-7924-1|page=491|quote=...strongly pro-Croatian during the entire interwar period, such as Hakija Hadzic and Alija Suljak, high school teachers, and Ademaga Mesic, a rich landowner. They were personal friends of Pavelic and vigorously promoted the Ustasha cause in Bosnia|date=October 2002}}</ref> Hadžić thanked Pavelić for the establishment of NDH, while Pavelić appointed Hadžić as his Commissioner for Bosnia.<ref name="Johnson2007">{{cite book|last=Johnson|first=Wes|authorlink=|title=Balkan inferno: betrayal, war and intervention, 1990-2005|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UbMWAQAAMAAJ|year=2007|publisher=Enigma Books|isbn=978-1-929631-63-6|page=163}}</ref><ref name="DedijerMiletić1990">{{cite book|last1=Dedijer|first1=Vladimir|authorlink1=Vladimir Dedijer|last2=Miletić|first2=Antun|authorlink2=Antun Miletić|title=Genocid nad Muslimanima, 1941-1945|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3_9mAAAAMAAJ|year=1990|publisher=Svjetlost|page=53|quote=Vladimir Dedijer, Antun Miletić. Hakija Hadžić izrazio je Paveliću zahvalnost na uspostavljanju NDH, a Pavelić je tom prilikom imenovao Hadžića za svoga povjerenika, a Božidara Bralu za njegovog zamjenika »nad cjelokupnom historijskom...}}</ref> Hadžić was Muslim Ustaša with highest rank in Sarajevo.{{sfn|Greble|2011|p=77}} Alija Nametak described Hadžić as one of extreme Croats, to distinguish them from people for whom their Croatian ethnic identity was less emphatic.{{sfn|Greble|2011|p=159}}

Hadžić claimed that he challenged [[Mehmed Spaho]] to a duel, while both of them were in [[Vienna]], but Spaho refused to appear.{{sfn|Kamberović|2009|p=13}} Hadžić denounced [[Džafer Kulenović]] too, although he also had a prominent position in the NDH.<ref name="Redžić2005">{{cite book|last=Redžić|first=Enver|authorlink=Enver Redžić|title=Bosnia and Herzegovina in the Second World War|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pVCx3jerQmYC&pg=PA167|year=2005|publisher=Psychology Press|isbn=978-0-7146-5625-0|page=167|quote=Although both held prominent positions in the NDH, Hakija Hadzic and Dzafer Kulenovic had little tolerance for one another. Hadzic denounced Kulenovic for ...}}</ref>

